00:04:53.030 --> 00:04:56.400
So before we go on,
let's review our history

00:04:56.400 --> 00:04:58.620
of the turntable
of the phonograph.

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:02.730
Remember 1877, Edison
comes out with his cylinder

00:05:02.730 --> 00:05:04.400
based recording mechanism.

00:05:04.400 --> 00:05:10.620
1887, Berliner releases
his disc based gramophone.

00:05:10.620 --> 00:05:15.040
The disc ultimately wins
out primarily because

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:20.250
of-- why, why did
the disk win out?

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:20.750
Yeah?

00:05:20.750 --> 00:05:22.791
AUDIENCE: Because you
could record more, and then

00:05:22.791 --> 00:05:27.724
because it was horizontal versus
vertical wedges, or edges,

00:05:27.724 --> 00:05:28.658
whatever.

00:05:28.658 --> 00:05:32.394
Basically it made
it so that amplitude

00:05:32.394 --> 00:05:33.800
wasn't really affected as much.

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:35.966
PROFESSOR: Well there's a
little bit more regularity

00:05:35.966 --> 00:05:39.670
in doing the transverse rather
than the lateral cut, right?

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:40.170
But--

00:05:40.170 --> 00:05:43.110
AUDIENCE: Isn't it easier to
encode larger amplitude swings

00:05:43.110 --> 00:05:45.320
with less amplification.

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:46.500
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:48.415
We can regulate the
amplitude more better

00:05:48.415 --> 00:05:50.960
and the cutting of the record,
but more importantly, we

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:52.510
can make copies.

00:05:52.510 --> 00:05:56.130
We can press copies super
easily of this flat disc

00:05:56.130 --> 00:06:00.260
and sell those
pre-recorded copies.

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:03.610
That's probably the number one
reason why the disc won out,

00:06:03.610 --> 00:06:05.100
because it was
easier to reproduce.

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:07.100
And we talked about that
as sort of a flattening

00:06:07.100 --> 00:06:09.032
of the dimensions of
the recording medium

00:06:09.032 --> 00:06:10.490
from three dimensions
on a cylinder

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:11.910
to two dimensions on a disc.

00:06:15.180 --> 00:06:18.880
By 1948 Columbia releases
the 33 and the third.

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:23.130
That's the large format LP, and
that gets back pretty much up

00:06:23.130 --> 00:06:25.670
to where we've talked about the
phonograph in the gramophone

00:06:25.670 --> 00:06:27.040
so far.

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:31.830
1969 Technics releases the
SP-10, the first direct drive

00:06:31.830 --> 00:06:32.990
turntable.

00:06:32.990 --> 00:06:35.720
This direct drive
mechanism turns out

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:38.060
to be a fairly important
technical feature.

00:06:38.060 --> 00:06:41.190
Previous turntables had
used a belt mechanism.

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:45.180
And the belt, while effective,
tended to wear out over time

00:06:45.180 --> 00:06:47.890
and slow down.

00:06:47.890 --> 00:06:50.100
The rate wasn't
always as constant

00:06:50.100 --> 00:06:52.640
and posed some other
technical problems.

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:55.640
With this direct
drive turntable,

00:06:55.640 --> 00:06:59.420
the performance of the turntable
was a little bit more rigorous

00:06:59.420 --> 00:07:02.930
and could handle a little
bit more abuse, namely,

00:07:02.930 --> 00:07:06.890
the kind of abuse we see
with contemporary practice.

00:07:06.890 --> 00:07:12.130
1969, Technics releases a less
expensive model, the SP-1100.

00:07:12.130 --> 00:07:15.130
1972 they release the SL-1200.

00:07:15.130 --> 00:07:17.420
And it's this
turntable that really

00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:20.290
defines the modern
turntable practice.

00:07:20.290 --> 00:07:23.430
If you go find a DJ
somewhere, and you

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:28.040
look at their turntables,
probably six to eight out of 10

00:07:28.040 --> 00:07:32.230
will be using this turntable
or some variation of it.

00:07:32.230 --> 00:07:35.840
Now they have the SL-1220
and SL-1260, et cetera.

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:39.120
But the SL-12 is still
the leading model

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:41.840
and, in fact, you'll hear
hip hop artists refer

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:46.390
to the SL-12 as the
turntable of choice.

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:49.840
This model allows you to select
different rotation speeds

00:07:49.840 --> 00:07:54.310
depending if you have a 78
or 45 or a 33 and a third.

00:07:54.310 --> 00:07:58.540
And it has this nice
variable speed adjustment

00:07:58.540 --> 00:08:00.440
slider here on the right.

00:08:00.440 --> 00:08:06.420
Why would you want to smoothly
vary the speed of playback?

00:08:06.420 --> 00:08:09.140
Slow things down,
speed things up.

00:08:09.140 --> 00:08:10.889
AUDIENCE: Skip ahead
to the next track.

00:08:10.889 --> 00:08:13.180
PROFESSOR: Fast forward,
well, yeah, you could do that.

00:08:13.180 --> 00:08:14.320
OK, that's one approach.

00:08:16.870 --> 00:08:19.190
Yeah you always just grab
the needle and throw it over.

00:08:19.190 --> 00:08:19.690
Yeah?

00:08:19.690 --> 00:08:21.150
AUDIENCE: If you're playing
two at the same time,

00:08:21.150 --> 00:08:23.070
if you want to get them
to be about the same pitch

00:08:23.070 --> 00:08:25.080
or if you want them to
be about the same speed,

00:08:25.080 --> 00:08:27.300
you can always just
adjust one smoothly.

00:08:27.300 --> 00:08:28.300
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:08:28.300 --> 00:08:31.320
By adjusting the rotation
speed here and changing

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:33.336
the rotation speed-- go ahead?

00:08:33.336 --> 00:08:35.419
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
if that was their intent

00:08:35.419 --> 00:08:39.409
or if it was actually
intended to just

00:08:39.409 --> 00:08:43.873
be able to adjust for
fluctuations in line frequency?

00:08:43.873 --> 00:08:46.028
Because, you know,
you may need to do

00:08:46.028 --> 00:08:48.670
that if you need it to go
exactly 33 and a third.

00:08:48.670 --> 00:08:50.420
PROFESSOR: I think
with the direct drive

00:08:50.420 --> 00:08:52.950
motor and the
modern design, they

00:08:52.950 --> 00:08:56.200
were able to pretty regularly
get the speed that they wanted.

00:08:56.200 --> 00:08:59.460
So I think the
motivation, maybe,

00:08:59.460 --> 00:09:01.320
and certainly the
most common use

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:03.960
is to match beats,
to match tempo.

00:09:03.960 --> 00:09:06.490
So that you could slow
down a track a little bit

00:09:06.490 --> 00:09:09.920
and move into another
track and match the beats,

00:09:09.920 --> 00:09:12.410
align the beats, which leads
to the whole practice of beat

00:09:12.410 --> 00:09:14.960
matching which used to
be done manually by ear

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:17.116
but is more often done
with software now.

00:09:17.116 --> 00:09:18.187
AUDIENCE: Were people
doing that in '69

00:09:18.187 --> 00:09:19.395
when this turntable came out?

00:09:19.395 --> 00:09:22.745
PROFESSOR: Not '69 but
the late '70s, early '80s.

00:09:22.745 --> 00:09:24.620
AUDIENCE: What's the
response to that ability

00:09:24.620 --> 00:09:26.571
or was the ability a
response to a desire?

00:09:26.571 --> 00:09:27.570
PROFESSOR: I'm not sure.

00:09:27.570 --> 00:09:30.865
That's a good thing to look at.

00:09:30.865 --> 00:09:33.390
This is a modern, this
isn't the 72 model.

00:09:33.390 --> 00:09:33.890
Yeah.

00:09:36.477 --> 00:09:38.060
I mean, that's a
great question to ask

00:09:38.060 --> 00:09:41.040
and something to look at.

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:45.620
Now combined with the modern
SL style of turntable,

00:09:45.620 --> 00:09:48.250
DJs often add a slip
mat, and this slip mat

00:09:48.250 --> 00:09:52.400
is really the, sort of, secret
ingredient to modern turntable

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:52.920
technique.

00:09:52.920 --> 00:09:54.570
It's simply a
circle of felt that

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:57.660
goes under the record
that permits the record

00:09:57.660 --> 00:10:00.830
to spin independently
of the platter.

00:10:00.830 --> 00:10:03.960
Now this allows us to
do a number of things

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:05.810
with our record.

00:10:05.810 --> 00:10:10.010
The so-called baby scratch is
the most basic scratch-- oops,

00:10:10.010 --> 00:10:14.010
this is the
transformers-- either way,

00:10:14.010 --> 00:10:16.620
we're going to look at a couple
scratches that don't require

00:10:16.620 --> 00:10:19.930
using the mixer, that
just employ manipulating

00:10:19.930 --> 00:10:21.900
the disc on the platter.

00:10:21.900 --> 00:10:25.625
And this is only possible
because of the felt of the slip

00:10:25.625 --> 00:10:28.990
mat, or at least, more possible.

00:10:28.990 --> 00:10:33.770
So this is the transformer--
oh, sorry, this is a bad clip.

00:10:33.770 --> 00:10:36.380
This is not what I wanted.

00:10:36.380 --> 00:10:36.880
Sorry.

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:40.315
Let's go to the phases,
maybe this is it.

00:10:40.315 --> 00:10:41.800
There we go.

00:10:41.800 --> 00:10:42.790
