00:12:37.640 --> 00:12:40.110
saying something, which often
gives those good white noise

00:12:40.110 --> 00:12:40.610
sounds.

00:12:40.610 --> 00:12:44.260
We'll hear more examples
of that in a little bit.

00:12:44.260 --> 00:12:48.100
Now the DJ mixer is one of
the other really important

00:12:48.100 --> 00:12:50.560
components of the
turntable's set up.

00:12:50.560 --> 00:12:54.610
And particularly,
the cross fader.

00:12:54.610 --> 00:12:59.080
The cross fader and the toggle
switches found on a modern DJ

00:12:59.080 --> 00:13:04.460
mixer allow the turntablist
to apply variable amplitude

00:13:04.460 --> 00:13:05.636
envelopes to the sound.

00:13:05.636 --> 00:13:07.260
We've already looked
at the development

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:08.520
of modular synthesizers.

00:13:08.520 --> 00:13:13.270
We can think of the cross
fader and the toggle switches,

00:13:13.270 --> 00:13:16.570
the cross fader located here
and the toggle switches located

00:13:16.570 --> 00:13:21.810
here, as various ways of
applying amplitude envelopes

00:13:21.810 --> 00:13:24.895
to the sound the DJ is
capturing from the disc.

00:13:27.450 --> 00:13:31.490
Now there's a wide
range of other tools

00:13:31.490 --> 00:13:34.070
available on the DJ mixer.

00:13:34.070 --> 00:13:36.640
Another important
one is the ability

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:41.240
to listen to more sources
than are being played.

00:13:41.240 --> 00:13:44.920
This is often described
as the queueing

00:13:44.920 --> 00:13:48.350
of the record or
the queue input.

00:13:48.350 --> 00:13:51.120
What this allows the DJ
to do is play one record

00:13:51.120 --> 00:13:53.850
and then play another
record and listen

00:13:53.850 --> 00:13:55.940
to that record in
their headphones

00:13:55.940 --> 00:13:58.090
before they play it
out to the audience.

00:13:58.090 --> 00:14:00.910
This leads to the sort
of stereotypical DJ

00:14:00.910 --> 00:14:06.430
pose of having one cup of a
headphone ear on their head

00:14:06.430 --> 00:14:07.970
while doing something.

00:14:07.970 --> 00:14:09.540
They're queuing up
the next record.

00:14:09.540 --> 00:14:12.130
They're listening to the next
record which may be a record

00:14:12.130 --> 00:14:15.020
or may be a digital audio file
or may be some other source,

00:14:15.020 --> 00:14:16.850
they're playing an
existing record,

00:14:16.850 --> 00:14:19.350
listening to another
record, adjusting

00:14:19.350 --> 00:14:21.910
where the records going to play,
maybe adjusting the playback

00:14:21.910 --> 00:14:24.840
speed, and doing that
all in the headphones

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:29.700
before they send that out to
the main mix to the house.

00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:32.020
So the ability to queue
up another channel

00:14:32.020 --> 00:14:36.000
before sending it out is a
critical feature of DJ mixers.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.140
Now some modern DJ mixers
have a wide variety

00:14:38.140 --> 00:14:39.550
of different effects.

00:14:39.550 --> 00:14:44.130
Some have delay, some have
reverb, some have samplers,

00:14:44.130 --> 00:14:45.880
some have various
other technologies.

00:14:45.880 --> 00:14:50.550
For instance, this Mackie d.2
features an optical cross fader

00:14:50.550 --> 00:14:54.170
which is advertised as never
changing its performance.

00:14:54.170 --> 00:14:57.530
The cross fader always
performs the same way

00:14:57.530 --> 00:14:58.880
because there's no friction.

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:00.380
There's other designs
that are using

00:15:00.380 --> 00:15:04.440
magnetic technologies
for the cross faders.

00:15:04.440 --> 00:15:09.560
This Numark DXM09 has some
beat synchronized affects

00:15:09.560 --> 00:15:11.480
so it allows you
to set the tempo

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:14.040
and then echos and
delays and other effects

00:15:14.040 --> 00:15:17.980
are synchronized to the beat
which is a pretty nice feature.

00:15:17.980 --> 00:15:22.200
This Numark 5000FX features
an integrated sampler

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:24.480
which allows you to, while
you're playing something,

00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:27.280
simply trigger a record,
sample something,

00:15:27.280 --> 00:15:30.096
and then play it back either
in reverse or forward later on,

00:15:30.096 --> 00:15:31.470
which as you
imagine, could offer

00:15:31.470 --> 00:15:33.780
some nice creative techniques.

00:15:33.780 --> 00:15:36.050
We already saw
another example where

00:15:36.050 --> 00:15:39.480
DJs work with something
like an MPC sampler.

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:43.260
So seeing a turntable next
to an MPC is not uncommon.

00:15:43.260 --> 00:15:45.750
Some DJs might work
with an external sampler

00:15:45.750 --> 00:15:48.520
next to their turntable,
but we do see some cases

00:15:48.520 --> 00:15:52.080
where the sampler is
integrated into the mixer.

00:15:52.080 --> 00:15:53.480
This device is very cool.

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:55.100
It seems to have
been discontinued,

00:15:55.100 --> 00:16:00.560
but this Vestax QFO
has a single turntable

00:16:00.560 --> 00:16:02.570
with a mixer built it.

00:16:02.570 --> 00:16:08.019
This provides a DJ to do a
solo set without a mixer.

00:16:08.019 --> 00:16:09.435
It has the essential
functionality

00:16:09.435 --> 00:16:14.890
of the cross fader of a mixer
built into the turntable

00:16:14.890 --> 00:16:17.580
so that with just this
and an MP3 player,

00:16:17.580 --> 00:16:19.740
you can put down
a background track

00:16:19.740 --> 00:16:24.140
and then scratch over this
and have your cross fader.

00:16:24.140 --> 00:16:27.510
Now working with the
turntable and the mixer

00:16:27.510 --> 00:16:30.100
is how most of the
turntable techniques

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:32.800
that we of have come about.

00:16:32.800 --> 00:16:35.630
I showed you guys some examples,
the baby and the waves,

00:16:35.630 --> 00:16:38.910
that don't use the mixer.

00:16:38.910 --> 00:16:42.690
These examples use the mixer to
create the various scratching

00:16:42.690 --> 00:16:43.640
techniques.

00:16:43.640 --> 00:16:45.806
So this is the one I
accidentally brought up before.

00:16:45.806 --> 00:16:47.060
This is a transformer.

00:16:47.060 --> 00:16:48.500
As you might expect,
this is named

00:16:48.500 --> 00:16:52.470
for making the type
of transforming sound.

00:17:06.910 --> 00:17:10.300
So there we're basically taking
a noise source from the record

00:17:10.300 --> 00:17:13.150
and then applying a
variable amplitude envelope

00:17:13.150 --> 00:17:16.690
to that noise source in
a rhythmic fashion which

00:17:16.690 --> 00:17:21.277
provides that very nice
quasi transformers sound.

00:17:21.277 --> 00:17:23.235
Or maybe they use it for
the real transformers,

00:17:23.235 --> 00:17:25.800
I'm not sure.

00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:28.140
The chirp, another technique,
check this one out,

00:17:28.140 --> 00:17:29.620
that makes use of
the cross faders.

00:17:29.620 --> 00:17:29.920
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:32.544
DJ QBERT: OK, this next scratch
is called a chirp scratch which

00:17:32.544 --> 00:17:35.812
was made popular by Jazzy Jeff
on a song called Magnificent.

00:17:35.812 --> 00:17:41.330
Jazzy Jeff made a whistle
sound like a bird.

00:17:41.330 --> 00:17:47.120
Anyway, this scratch is kind of
tricky so you let a sound play,

00:17:47.120 --> 00:17:51.842
and you've got to turn it off
right when it plays and just

00:17:51.842 --> 00:17:57.857
move your hand backward
in, like, a mirror fashion.

00:17:57.857 --> 00:17:58.690
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:17:58.690 --> 00:18:02.000
PROFESSOR: Can anybody summarise
what that technique is there?

00:18:06.976 --> 00:18:09.475
We'll listen to it a little bit
more then you can try again.

00:18:09.475 --> 00:18:10.141
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:18:10.141 --> 00:18:15.525
DJ QBERT: And then turn
it off and take it back.

00:18:15.525 --> 00:18:16.358
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:18:16.358 --> 00:18:19.810
AUDIENCE: It seems like it's
basically amplitude modulation

00:18:19.810 --> 00:18:23.440
or modulating the amplitude
with a really high attack.

00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:25.024
PROFESSOR: Well the
attack is gradual.

00:18:25.024 --> 00:18:26.856
You can see that the
attack of the amplitude

00:18:26.856 --> 00:18:27.640
is gradual, right?

00:18:27.640 --> 00:18:30.110
You can see him feeding it in.

00:18:30.110 --> 00:18:32.310
Anybody else want to
take a stab at describing

00:18:32.310 --> 00:18:33.735
what this technique is?

00:18:33.735 --> 00:18:35.620
AUDIENCE: Without
saying what he just did?

00:18:35.620 --> 00:18:37.340
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:18:37.340 --> 00:18:40.540
It basically links
amplitude and pitch.

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:44.550
So amplitude is faded in
as the record is sped up,

00:18:44.550 --> 00:18:48.120
and then amplitude is faded
out as a record is slowed down.

00:18:48.120 --> 00:18:49.780
So those two
parameters are linked,

00:18:49.780 --> 00:18:52.240
and that allows him to create
this distinctive sound.

00:18:56.021 --> 00:18:56.520
Right?

00:18:56.520 --> 00:18:59.430
So amplitude and the change
in playback speed are linked.

00:19:03.159 --> 00:19:04.075
Ever hear that before?

00:19:08.730 --> 00:19:11.470
Of course, DJ Qbert's
quite good at this.

00:19:11.470 --> 00:19:13.810
The crab gives us
an example of some

00:19:13.810 --> 00:19:17.070
of the really crazy
extended techniques that

00:19:17.070 --> 00:19:19.050
develop using the cross fader.

00:19:19.050 --> 00:19:21.680
If you've ever seen a
Flamenco guitarist use

00:19:21.680 --> 00:19:25.730
all their fingers, this
should remind you of this.

00:19:25.730 --> 00:19:27.266
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:19:27.266 --> 00:19:28.682
DJ QBERT: Where I
use two fingers,

00:19:28.682 --> 00:19:30.158
and instead of
using two fingers,

00:19:30.158 --> 00:19:33.602
why don't you use five fingers.?

00:19:33.602 --> 00:19:36.080
So instead of the
tapping like a twiddle,

00:19:36.080 --> 00:19:38.320
it's slide your
fingers across kind

00:19:38.320 --> 00:19:39.745
of like snapping my fingers.

00:19:39.745 --> 00:19:42.595
PROFESSOR: Easy, right?

00:19:42.595 --> 00:19:46.664
DJ QBERT: And it was actually
called the [INAUDIBLE] scratch

00:19:46.664 --> 00:19:49.620
because me and him [INAUDIBLE]

00:19:49.620 --> 00:19:51.286
PROFESSOR: OK, it
goes on a little long.

00:19:51.286 --> 00:19:52.744
DJ QBERT: This is
the crab scratch.

00:20:00.302 --> 00:20:01.010
PROFESSOR: Right?

00:20:01.010 --> 00:20:02.844
You guys can go home
and do that now, right?

00:20:02.844 --> 00:20:03.676
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:20:03.676 --> 00:20:05.370
You just use your
thumb as a spring.

00:20:09.870 --> 00:20:11.690
But that's a great
example of how

00:20:11.690 --> 00:20:15.210
the DJ mixer and particularly
the cross fader combined

00:20:15.210 --> 00:20:20.310
with the variable
playback of the turntable

00:20:20.310 --> 00:20:22.740
really provides a wide
range of different sounds.

00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:25.540
Again, we can think of it
as having variable playback

00:20:25.540 --> 00:20:29.060
speed and some frequency
modulation from the turntable.

00:20:29.060 --> 00:20:31.440
And we can think of the mixer
as providing a way for us

00:20:31.440 --> 00:20:35.080
to play envelopes and
do amplitude modulation

00:20:35.080 --> 00:20:36.770
to our sounds.

00:20:36.770 --> 00:20:37.385
Questions?

00:20:37.385 --> 00:20:37.885
Yeah.

00:20:37.885 --> 00:20:39.480
AUDIENCE: The design of
like two disc turntables

00:20:39.480 --> 00:20:41.240
with the cross
fader was something

00:20:41.240 --> 00:20:43.990
just for queueing and
playing for parties,

00:20:43.990 --> 00:20:45.850
and they made it spinning later?

00:20:45.850 --> 00:20:47.656
PROFESSOR: The
original cross fader?

00:20:47.656 --> 00:20:48.280
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:20:48.280 --> 00:20:48.946
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:20:48.946 --> 00:20:51.130
It came out of,
I think, the need

00:20:51.130 --> 00:20:54.464
to want to have two records
and have continuous music.

00:20:54.464 --> 00:20:55.880
AUDIENCE: But they
had these kinds

00:20:55.880 --> 00:20:58.010
of things in radio
stations long before--

00:20:58.010 --> 00:20:59.468
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
we're going to get

00:20:59.468 --> 00:21:02.710
to some examples of why
that came about in a bit.

00:21:02.710 --> 00:21:05.580
So when we look at the
development of hip hop,

00:21:05.580 --> 00:21:08.250
and we look at the
development of turntablism,

00:21:08.250 --> 00:21:10.090
it's essential for
us to look back

00:21:10.090 --> 00:21:14.930
to the foundations in
Jamaican sound systems.

00:21:14.930 --> 00:21:20.830
Many of the modern practices
of turntablism, of DJ culture,

00:21:20.830 --> 00:21:24.360
come out of the
Jamaican traditions.

00:21:24.360 --> 00:21:30.310
You may not know that in
the '50s and into the '60s,

00:21:30.310 --> 00:21:33.210
the Jamaicans
developed a wide range

00:21:33.210 --> 00:21:35.110
of different musical
practices and developed

00:21:35.110 --> 00:21:39.210
a very large and robust
recording studio system where

00:21:39.210 --> 00:21:40.630
there were numerous
studios, there

00:21:40.630 --> 00:21:43.910
were numerous independent
Jamaican releases, not only of

00:21:43.910 --> 00:21:47.630
reggae, but a wide variety
of other musical genres.

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:51.650
The genres that we are
concerned about come out

00:21:51.650 --> 00:21:55.692
of a tradition from these
things called sound systems.

00:21:55.692 --> 00:21:57.150
Now you may think
of a sound system

00:21:57.150 --> 00:21:59.340
as a sort of boom
box or something

00:21:59.340 --> 00:22:01.880
you buy at the store, that's
essentially what these were.

00:22:01.880 --> 00:22:04.450
But, at the time in
Jamaica, not everybody

00:22:04.450 --> 00:22:07.940
had access to turntables
or amplifiers and speakers,

00:22:07.940 --> 00:22:12.350
so those that did
started to hold parties.

00:22:12.350 --> 00:22:16.440
And they would have a
sound system, a turntable,

00:22:16.440 --> 00:22:19.140
and speakers, and
amplifier, and would

00:22:19.140 --> 00:22:21.850
use these as community
record players.

00:22:21.850 --> 00:22:25.480
People would get together and
dance, have fun, have a party,

00:22:25.480 --> 00:22:28.850
and this really led to the
culture of the person who

00:22:28.850 --> 00:22:32.480
ran the sound system being in
charge of providing the music,

00:22:32.480 --> 00:22:34.370
being in charge of
running the party,

00:22:34.370 --> 00:22:37.750
being in charge of
selecting the music.

00:22:37.750 --> 00:22:41.670
The DJs even began to be known
as selectors because they would

00:22:41.670 --> 00:22:44.640
select the music being played.

00:22:44.640 --> 00:22:49.210
Clement Dodd, aka
Coxsone, was credited

00:22:49.210 --> 00:22:52.900
with the invention of
this sound system concept.

00:22:52.900 --> 00:22:55.230
In the 1950s, he established
a sound system called

00:22:55.230 --> 00:22:58.590
the downbeat sound
system, and he later on

00:22:58.590 --> 00:23:02.850
went to open Studio One
in Kingston in 1963.

00:23:02.850 --> 00:23:06.320
So we have this sort
of mixture of somebody

00:23:06.320 --> 00:23:08.920
who starts off sort of as
a performer, as kind of

00:23:08.920 --> 00:23:12.590
like a party organizer,
then moving into the studio

00:23:12.590 --> 00:23:16.240
and becoming a producer and
a studio engineer working

00:23:16.240 --> 00:23:19.230
with people like Bob
Marley and others.

00:23:19.230 --> 00:23:22.290
Now the Jamaican
recording industry

00:23:22.290 --> 00:23:24.400
was very active in the 1960s.

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:29.410
They would often release
b-sides of 45 RPM singles.

00:23:29.410 --> 00:23:33.040
These b-sides, very often,
were instrumental versions

00:23:33.040 --> 00:23:36.220
of the a-side track.

00:23:36.220 --> 00:23:38.820
And these b-sides
offered an opportunity

00:23:38.820 --> 00:23:41.690
for people to remix
and experiment

00:23:41.690 --> 00:23:44.440
with these instrumental tracks.

00:23:44.440 --> 00:23:48.250
Two types of experimentation
went on with these b-sides.

00:23:48.250 --> 00:23:51.390
One involved manipulating
the sound on these records

00:23:51.390 --> 00:23:57.830
and producing remixes and, what
we later began to call, dub.

00:23:57.830 --> 00:24:00.130
Another practice that
came out of these b-sides

00:24:00.130 --> 00:24:04.950
was vocalizations, spoken word
over these instrumental tracks.

00:24:04.950 --> 00:24:08.810
And many credit the development
of the spoken word traditions,

00:24:08.810 --> 00:24:13.160
often called toasting, as one
of the foundations of modern hip

00:24:13.160 --> 00:24:14.730
hop.

00:24:14.730 --> 00:24:18.770
So musicians such
as King Tubby would

00:24:18.770 --> 00:24:23.490
take either these instrumental
b-sides or four channel source

00:24:23.490 --> 00:24:25.240
tracks and remix them.

00:24:25.240 --> 00:24:27.940
And using basic
studio processors

00:24:27.940 --> 00:24:30.080
available at the time,
things like reverbs,

00:24:30.080 --> 00:24:32.920
echo machines, and
the like, often things

00:24:32.920 --> 00:24:36.500
as simple as variable low
pass and high pass filters,

00:24:36.500 --> 00:24:41.150
they would remix tunes
and often manipulate

00:24:41.150 --> 00:24:43.260
the vocals, manipulate
the instruments,

00:24:43.260 --> 00:24:45.670
in a way that created
these instrumental

00:24:45.670 --> 00:24:48.550
tunes that we know as dub.

00:24:48.550 --> 00:24:52.110
One of the pieces we listened
to for today's class,

00:24:52.110 --> 00:24:55.110
"555 Dub Street,"
is a collaboration

00:24:55.110 --> 00:24:58.340
between Augustus
Pablo and King Tubby.

00:24:58.340 --> 00:25:00.780
Pablo was known
for his performance

00:25:00.780 --> 00:25:03.020
on-- what instrument
was that in this piece?

00:25:05.822 --> 00:25:07.970
Is it up there?

00:25:07.970 --> 00:25:11.570
The melodica, an instrument
where you blow air

00:25:11.570 --> 00:25:13.885
into a small little
keyboard that

00:25:13.885 --> 00:25:16.010
allows you to control the
amplitude with your mouth

00:25:16.010 --> 00:25:17.740
and change pitch
with your fingers.

00:25:17.740 --> 00:25:22.910
Augustus Pablo performed
on the melodica

00:25:22.910 --> 00:25:25.560
on produced whole recordings.

00:25:25.560 --> 00:25:29.090
And in this track, King Tubby
comes in and sort of remixed

00:25:29.090 --> 00:25:32.570
and modifies this track
on top of all of that.

00:25:32.570 --> 00:25:36.350
Let's listen to a
little bit of this.

00:25:36.350 --> 00:25:39.455
[MUSIC - AUGUSTUS PABLO, "555
 DUB STREET"]

00:25:46.337 --> 00:25:48.670
PROFESSOR: OK, right there,
what did we just hear there?

00:25:48.670 --> 00:25:50.725
AUDIENCE: That's the melodica.

00:25:50.725 --> 00:25:52.600
PROFESSOR: Yeah that's
the melodica entrance,

00:25:52.600 --> 00:25:54.922
but did the melodica
sound normal?

00:25:54.922 --> 00:25:57.991
What was going on?

00:25:57.991 --> 00:25:58.990
AUDIENCE: Some feedback.

00:25:58.990 --> 00:26:01.100
PROFESSOR: A feedback,
a delay, there's

00:26:01.100 --> 00:26:04.920
a delay that has a high
feedback level that's making it

00:26:04.920 --> 00:26:06.540
you hear an initial
sound, and then it

00:26:06.540 --> 00:26:08.256
continues into a
constant texture.

00:26:08.256 --> 00:26:09.380
Let's listen to that again.

00:26:09.380 --> 00:26:12.785
That's probably one of the
most signature sounds of dug.

00:26:12.785 --> 00:26:17.090
First we have a beat, of course,
but then this use of delay

00:26:17.090 --> 00:26:19.980
and echo to smear a sound.

00:26:19.980 --> 00:26:21.526
Let's listen to that again.

00:26:21.526 --> 00:26:24.977
[MUSIC - AUGUSTUS PABLO, "555
 DUB STREET"]

00:26:38.140 --> 00:26:39.350
PROFESSOR: Right there.

00:26:39.350 --> 00:26:41.010
What we just heard
there can be done

00:26:41.010 --> 00:26:42.380
with basic studio equipment.

00:26:42.380 --> 00:26:43.580
You need a delay unit.

00:26:43.580 --> 00:26:44.880
You need some faders.

00:26:44.880 --> 00:26:49.440
You send the signal to the
delay unit with a high feedback.

00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:52.160
It starts to feedback and
produce that continuous sound.

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:54.825
And then he dropped the source
signal the rest of the beat

00:26:54.825 --> 00:26:58.160
so we got that very nice gesture
where we had the feedback going

00:26:58.160 --> 00:27:00.950
on of the melodica and
then beat drops out,

00:27:00.950 --> 00:27:04.700
the beat comes back in, a little
anticipation and response.

00:27:04.700 --> 00:27:06.182
Let's hear that again.

00:27:06.182 --> 00:27:09.640
[MUSIC - AUGUSTUS PABLO, "555
 DUB STREET"]

00:27:31.870 --> 00:27:35.100
PROFESSOR: What did we just
hear on the high hats there?

00:27:35.100 --> 00:27:36.020
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:36.020 --> 00:27:36.410
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:27:36.410 --> 00:27:36.910
Yeah.

00:27:36.910 --> 00:27:38.250
Moving the filters.

00:27:38.250 --> 00:27:42.830
Maybe a peak notch or parametric
filter or a low or high pass

00:27:42.830 --> 00:27:46.200
filter with a high resonance
moving across the high hats

00:27:46.200 --> 00:27:49.580
to create that change in timbre,
another very common technique.

00:27:49.580 --> 00:27:54.650
[MUSIC - AUGUSTUS PABLO, "555
 DUB STREET"]

00:27:54.650 --> 00:27:58.560
PROFESSOR: So dub exploited
these relatively simple

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:03.060
techniques of cutting
in and out of parts

00:28:03.060 --> 00:28:08.460
using feedback and delay, using
variable filters to create

00:28:08.460 --> 00:28:11.950
really interesting
instrumental music.

00:28:11.950 --> 00:28:13.680
That was one tradition
that came out

00:28:13.680 --> 00:28:15.200
of the Jamaican sound systems.

00:28:15.200 --> 00:28:21.430
Another is this focus on
taking an instrumental track

00:28:21.430 --> 00:28:24.900
and doing something over
that instrumental track.

00:28:24.900 --> 00:28:27.930
In the sound system tradition,
the leaders of the sound system

00:28:27.930 --> 00:28:31.350
would want to encourage
people at their party

00:28:31.350 --> 00:28:33.300
to have a good time
and often would

00:28:33.300 --> 00:28:36.360
start toasting or shouting
out to the audience

00:28:36.360 --> 00:28:37.860
as the music was playing.

00:28:37.860 --> 00:28:40.550
Often these toasts
would be rhythmitized

00:28:40.550 --> 00:28:42.260
chants of some sort.

00:28:42.260 --> 00:28:43.820
And as I said
before, many people

00:28:43.820 --> 00:28:49.670
credit this as a key
development to the existence

00:28:49.670 --> 00:28:51.840
of American hip hop.

00:28:51.840 --> 00:28:54.710
But more than the sound
system the key person

00:28:54.710 --> 00:28:57.060
that's often looked
to as connecting

00:28:57.060 --> 00:29:00.310
Jamaican sound system
traditions to American hip hop

00:29:00.310 --> 00:29:04.450
is DJ Kool Herc, Clive Campbell.

00:29:04.450 --> 00:29:06.760
If we think back to the
People Under the Stairs track

00:29:06.760 --> 00:29:08.430
we started with,
people who still

00:29:08.430 --> 00:29:11.590
live in the folklore of DJ
Kool Herc, the first person

00:29:11.590 --> 00:29:12.810
they mention.

00:29:12.810 --> 00:29:17.930
Herc moved to the Bronx from
Jamaica in the late '60s

00:29:17.930 --> 00:29:23.560
and really transplanted
this sound system concept.

00:29:23.560 --> 00:29:26.190
He began throwing parties
in the South Bronx.

00:29:26.190 --> 00:29:28.530
He worked with an
MC, Coke La Rock who

00:29:28.530 --> 00:29:32.010
would do some of the
toasting and began

00:29:32.010 --> 00:29:35.490
experimenting with using
two turntables each

00:29:35.490 --> 00:29:38.930
with the same recorded material.

00:29:38.930 --> 00:29:40.810
This led him to
develop a technique

00:29:40.810 --> 00:29:43.930
that he called the merry
go round which allowed him

00:29:43.930 --> 00:29:48.750
to cut back and
forth between two

00:29:48.750 --> 00:29:51.930
excerpts from the
same record and extend

00:29:51.930 --> 00:29:55.310
the music for the
sake of dancing,

00:29:55.310 --> 00:29:57.350
for the sake of the party.

00:29:57.350 --> 00:30:01.430
In an excellent interview
with Terry Gross from 2005,

00:30:01.430 --> 00:30:04.180
he describes this technique
and the development

00:30:04.180 --> 00:30:08.990
of his practice in
detail better than I can.

00:30:08.990 --> 00:30:12.054
So let's listen to a
little bit of this.

00:30:12.054 --> 00:30:12.720
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:30:12.720 --> 00:30:14.520
TERRY GROSS: You're such an
interesting figure in hip hop.

00:30:14.520 --> 00:30:16.150
Everyone who was
there in the beginning

00:30:16.150 --> 00:30:18.660
seems to agree that
you started it all.

00:30:18.660 --> 00:30:20.990
But because you never
recorded, in some ways

00:30:20.990 --> 00:30:22.985
you're more of a cult
figure than a star.

00:30:28.704 --> 00:30:31.668
KOOL HERC: That's why it
got to be called exclusive.

00:30:31.668 --> 00:30:33.644
So you can tell everybody
because [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:38.990 --> 00:30:41.420
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:30:41.420 --> 00:30:43.280
PROFESSOR: So what
do you guys think?

00:30:43.280 --> 00:30:45.410
Impressions, ideas, surprises?

00:30:45.410 --> 00:30:46.784
AUDIENCE: He looks
like Ludacris.

00:30:46.784 --> 00:30:48.410
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
ha ha, that's true.

00:30:48.410 --> 00:30:49.994
AUDIENCE: He really
feels responsible.

00:30:49.994 --> 00:30:50.868
PROFESSOR: Say again?

00:30:50.868 --> 00:30:53.090
AUDIENCE: He really feels
responsible for keeping

00:30:53.090 --> 00:30:54.660
people happy.

00:30:54.660 --> 00:30:55.670
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:30:55.670 --> 00:30:57.390
Yeah his attitude
about what's supposed

00:30:57.390 --> 00:31:01.180
to go on at these
meetings, at these parties

00:31:01.180 --> 00:31:07.070
is different than we think of
many hip hop or DJ performers

00:31:07.070 --> 00:31:07.880
these days.

00:31:07.880 --> 00:31:11.300
It's not about himself--
well, it is, you see the pride

00:31:11.300 --> 00:31:14.620
he has-- but it's also
about, well, he's a shepherd.

00:31:14.620 --> 00:31:18.300
This idea that he's really
concerned about getting people

00:31:18.300 --> 00:31:19.710
to have a good time.

00:31:19.710 --> 00:31:24.610
His attention to his audience
is what led to his interest

00:31:24.610 --> 00:31:26.640
in the merry go
round in the breaks.

00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:29.550
What is he talking about there,
this merry go around technique?

00:31:29.550 --> 00:31:30.725
Ideas?

00:31:30.725 --> 00:31:32.975
And these breaks, first of
all, what are these breaks?

00:31:37.820 --> 00:31:39.820
AUDIENCE: What he was
saying is that people have

00:31:39.820 --> 00:31:42.122
their favorite parts of
the songs that they were

00:31:42.122 --> 00:31:45.632
able to dance to and that have
a little special move and a way

00:31:45.632 --> 00:31:47.630
to do that special
move, and so he just

00:31:47.630 --> 00:31:50.197
figured why not repeat it over
and over again so you can get

00:31:50.197 --> 00:31:52.530
people back on the dance
floor, play their special move.

00:31:52.530 --> 00:31:54.196
PROFESSOR: That's
right the breaks would

00:31:54.196 --> 00:31:57.350
be the instrumental break
in a tune, a place where

00:31:57.350 --> 00:32:00.080
the vocals would drop out,
and the rhythm section

00:32:00.080 --> 00:32:01.042
would come forward.

00:32:01.042 --> 00:32:03.042
These would generally be
relatively short, 4, 8,

00:32:03.042 --> 00:32:06.860
16 bars, relatively short parts
where the rhythm section would

00:32:06.860 --> 00:32:10.190
come forward, and these would
have a little bit more energy.

00:32:10.190 --> 00:32:13.720
And Herc realized that this
inspired people dance more.

00:32:13.720 --> 00:32:16.710
So he developed a technique
to extend the breaks.

00:32:16.710 --> 00:32:21.230
His technique was to use two
copies of the same record,

00:32:21.230 --> 00:32:24.900
and then while one was playing,
he could spin the other back

00:32:24.900 --> 00:32:28.710
and play the other and switch
back and forth between two

00:32:28.710 --> 00:32:31.620
records with the same
material and extend the break.

00:32:31.620 --> 00:32:35.480
He called this the merry
go round technique.

00:32:35.480 --> 00:32:39.810
This led to a whole
attention to these breaks,

00:32:39.810 --> 00:32:45.070
and he mentions a very important
one called Apache which is also

00:32:45.070 --> 00:32:48.510
mentioned by our
friends the People

00:32:48.510 --> 00:32:51.440
Under the Stairs in their track.

00:32:51.440 --> 00:32:55.420
So let's look at this.

00:32:55.420 --> 00:32:57.950
The link for the whole
interview is there.

00:32:57.950 --> 00:33:00.250
It's really a great interview.

00:33:00.250 --> 00:33:02.590
So, Apache, every b-boy knew it.

00:33:02.590 --> 00:33:08.110
Apache, probably the most
famous break of all breaks.

00:33:08.110 --> 00:33:10.435
It has a long and
complicated history.

00:33:10.435 --> 00:33:14.750
A study of the history of
Apache was done by an author

00:33:14.750 --> 00:33:18.620
by the name Matos called,
"All Roads Lead to Apache."

00:33:18.620 --> 00:33:21.010
You can find the
complete article here.

00:33:21.010 --> 00:33:22.720
The history of this
tune is complex

00:33:22.720 --> 00:33:24.390
and comes from various sources.

00:33:24.390 --> 00:33:30.150
In 1960 there were two
versions of this tune, Apache,

00:33:30.150 --> 00:33:35.160
that don't bear much relation to
what we think of now as Apache,

00:33:35.160 --> 00:33:37.387
but we can hear a
little bit of these.

00:33:37.387 --> 00:33:40.369
[MUSIC - BERT WEEDON, "APACHE"]

00:34:01.243 --> 00:34:03.231
PROFESSOR: Ever hear
that melody before?

00:34:03.231 --> 00:34:04.740
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:34:04.740 --> 00:34:09.080
PROFESSOR: So that was one
version by Bert Weedon.

00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:11.219
Cliff Richard and the
Shadows did another version

00:34:11.219 --> 00:34:12.988
closely related to that version.

00:34:12.988 --> 00:34:15.071
AUDIENCE: Do you think
that's closer to rockabilly

00:34:15.071 --> 00:34:16.490
or closer to like Jamaican?

00:34:16.490 --> 00:34:18.770
[MUSIC - CLIFF RICHARD AND THE
 SHADOWS, "APACHE"]

00:34:18.770 --> 00:34:20.603
PROFESSOR: It's hard
to describe what it is.

00:34:23.194 --> 00:34:24.360
It's hard to say what it is.

00:34:24.360 --> 00:34:27.350
But you'll see where it gets
into hip hop in a second.

00:34:27.350 --> 00:34:30.496
So here we hear the same melody,
slightly different rhythm

00:34:30.496 --> 00:34:30.996
section.

00:34:36.960 --> 00:34:39.760
Now those were the sort
of foundations of Apache.

00:34:39.760 --> 00:34:45.840
It was the incredible bongo band
with their album, "Bongo Rock"

00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:49.090
that provided the break that
excited people like Herc

00:34:49.090 --> 00:34:51.130
and so many others later on.

00:34:51.130 --> 00:34:54.260
You'll hear the same melody
there from the 1960 tunes,

00:34:54.260 --> 00:34:58.200
but here he adds this
bongo rhythm section

00:34:58.200 --> 00:35:00.617
that caught a lot of
people's attention.

00:35:00.617 --> 00:35:04.593
[MUSIC - INCREDIBLE BONGO BAND,
 "APACHE"]

00:35:16.679 --> 00:35:18.012
PROFESSOR: It's the same melody.

00:35:21.990 --> 00:35:24.280
But that opening bongo
rhythm is the thing

00:35:24.280 --> 00:35:25.650
that excited people so much.

00:35:25.650 --> 00:35:27.970
So shortly after
the Sugarhill Gang

00:35:27.970 --> 00:35:30.320
produces, the first to
put this in something

00:35:30.320 --> 00:35:33.016
more like a hip hop context.

00:35:33.016 --> 00:35:37.000
[MUSIC - SUGARHILL GANG,
 "APACHE"]

00:35:57.040 --> 00:35:58.290
PROFESSOR: There's the melody.

00:36:13.368 --> 00:36:15.117
AUDIENCE: It's like
two minutes like that.

00:36:15.117 --> 00:36:15.783
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:36:34.450 --> 00:36:36.160
Now, of course, a
whole study could

00:36:36.160 --> 00:36:38.840
be done not only on the
evolution of this tune,

00:36:38.840 --> 00:36:42.400
but the distant and complex
associations and references

00:36:42.400 --> 00:36:45.864
to ideas about Native
American culture which

00:36:45.864 --> 00:36:47.280
are irrelevant in
this discussion.

00:36:47.280 --> 00:36:50.980
But we are just focusing
on this one peculiar bongo

00:36:50.980 --> 00:36:53.550
rhythm which comes
back again and again.

00:36:53.550 --> 00:36:56.070
Future sound of London,
not a hip hop group,

00:36:56.070 --> 00:36:57.840
use it in this example.

00:36:57.840 --> 00:36:59.782
Here it's a little sped up

00:36:59.782 --> 00:37:01.030
[MUSIC - FUTURE SOUND OF LONDON,
 "WE HAVE EXPLOSIVES"]

00:37:01.030 --> 00:37:03.490
PROFESSOR: And there's some
other things going on there.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:39.360
And A very clear example
from 2002 by The Roots

00:37:39.360 --> 00:37:42.539
which starts off right with
that Apache bongo rhythm.

00:37:42.539 --> 00:37:46.032
[MUSIC - THE ROOTS, "THOUGHT @
 WORK"]

00:38:01.010 --> 00:38:04.030
PROFESSOR: So the
Incredible Bongo Band,

00:38:04.030 --> 00:38:07.540
one of the most popular
breaks there is.

00:38:07.540 --> 00:38:11.990
Another popular break is often
referred to as the amen break.

00:38:11.990 --> 00:38:16.820
This again was nicely
taken into a single context

00:38:16.820 --> 00:38:20.530
by the study of someone,
this one was this guy named,

00:38:20.530 --> 00:38:24.350
Harrison, this idea of
studying the history of a break

00:38:24.350 --> 00:38:27.650
as looking at the lineage of
either a sample or a break,

00:38:27.650 --> 00:38:32.920
I think, is a really interesting
approach to studying music.

00:38:32.920 --> 00:38:35.320
He produced this little audio
documentary called, "Can I

00:38:35.320 --> 00:38:40.070
Get An Amen" where he
looks at this 4 bar

00:38:40.070 --> 00:38:43.210
drum solo from this group
called, The Winstons, that

00:38:43.210 --> 00:38:46.110
was found on a track on
the b-side, a relatively

00:38:46.110 --> 00:38:49.330
unknown tune that
sounded like this.

00:38:49.330 --> 00:38:52.240
[MUSIC - THE WINSTONS, "AMEN
 BROTHER"]

00:39:01.940 --> 00:39:03.440
So there we can
really clearly hear

00:39:03.440 --> 00:39:06.440
the break, the part where
the brass section drops out

00:39:06.440 --> 00:39:08.690
and the rhythm
section steps forward.

00:39:08.690 --> 00:39:10.800
Does that beat sound
familiar to anybody?

00:39:10.800 --> 00:39:12.170
Ever hear something like that?

00:39:12.170 --> 00:39:15.180
Maybe all over the place.

00:39:15.180 --> 00:39:17.870
The Nate Harrison
documentary nicely

00:39:17.870 --> 00:39:21.220
describes the different
ways that this was used,

00:39:21.220 --> 00:39:24.340
not only how it was used
in its original form,

00:39:24.340 --> 00:39:27.530
but how was chopped up,
sold, and commodified

00:39:27.530 --> 00:39:30.240
in various sampler
libraries and other tools

00:39:30.240 --> 00:39:32.790
that people bought
and rearranged.

00:39:32.790 --> 00:39:35.376
Some quick examples
of this beat.

00:39:35.376 --> 00:39:37.250
Different artists use
this in different ways.

00:39:37.250 --> 00:39:38.666
Some of the
connections he suggest

00:39:38.666 --> 00:39:40.220
are maybe a little
bit more distant.

00:39:40.220 --> 00:39:41.740
Like the idea of
this beat, I think,

00:39:41.740 --> 00:39:44.180
is used sometimes as much
as the original beat,

00:39:44.180 --> 00:39:46.300
but we can hear a
little bit of this

00:39:46.300 --> 00:39:50.280
in "Straight Outta
Compton" by N.W.A.

00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:52.950
[MUSIC - N.W.A., "STRAIGHT OUTTA
 COMPTON"]

00:39:56.750 --> 00:39:59.980
PROFESSOR: We can hear a bit
of the first bar of that beat.

00:40:05.920 --> 00:40:08.170
Mantronix, "King of the Beats."

00:40:08.170 --> 00:40:12.170
[MUSIC - MANTRONIX, "KING OF THE
 BEATS"]

00:40:16.920 --> 00:40:17.675
PROFESSOR: Shy FX.

00:40:17.675 --> 00:40:20.880
[MUSIC - SHY FX, "ORIGINAL
 NATTAH"]

00:40:23.965 --> 00:40:27.020
PROFESSOR: Here we see that
Amen break start to be cut up

00:40:27.020 --> 00:40:29.020
and rearranged a little bit.

00:40:29.020 --> 00:40:30.430
That's also very popular.

00:40:30.430 --> 00:40:33.208
[MUSIC - L DOUBLE &amp; YOUNGBLOOD,
 "NEW STYLE"]

00:40:36.312 --> 00:40:37.770
PROFESSOR: Now
Harrison goes as far

00:40:37.770 --> 00:40:41.580
to suggest that that beat led
to whole genres of music that

00:40:41.580 --> 00:40:44.320
use that style of beat
which gets a little bit more

00:40:44.320 --> 00:40:45.840
of a distant
connection, but I think

00:40:45.840 --> 00:40:48.170
there's something to be
said for that approach.

00:40:48.170 --> 00:40:51.350
Harrison also points
out that this sample was

00:40:51.350 --> 00:40:54.909
sold in sample packs and
available commercially

00:40:54.909 --> 00:40:56.950
which leads to all sorts
of interesting questions

00:40:56.950 --> 00:41:00.080
about copyright and has this
nice example from a Jeep

00:41:00.080 --> 00:41:03.450
commercial in California that
uses this beat to suggest-- I

00:41:03.450 --> 00:41:06.670
don't know-- the rugged
freedom of driving your Jeep

00:41:06.670 --> 00:41:09.696
to go skiing or something.

00:41:09.696 --> 00:41:13.505
[VIDEO PLAYBACK, JEEP
 COMMERCIAL]

00:41:17.159 --> 00:41:18.950
PROFESSOR: Hear it in
the background there?

00:41:23.720 --> 00:41:24.530
Ha ha.

00:41:24.530 --> 00:41:26.426
AUDIENCE: Driving
straight outta Compton?

00:41:26.426 --> 00:41:29.850
PROFESSOR: Ha ha.

00:41:29.850 --> 00:41:32.240
Now back to the People
Under the Stairs.

00:41:32.240 --> 00:41:35.140
People who still live in the
folklore of DJ Kool Herc.

00:41:35.140 --> 00:41:36.310
We talked about Herc.

00:41:36.310 --> 00:41:38.910
Bam is a reference
to Africa Bambaataa.

00:41:38.910 --> 00:41:42.370
We talked about Africa
Bambaataa earlier.

00:41:42.370 --> 00:41:45.990
Grand Wizard Theodore
is often credited

00:41:45.990 --> 00:41:48.242
for inventing the scratch.

00:41:48.242 --> 00:41:50.200
And whether or not this
is true is hard to say,

00:41:50.200 --> 00:41:53.870
but the story goes, he was
hanging out in his basement

00:41:53.870 --> 00:42:00.210
listening to a record, and his
mom yelled, hey Grand Wizard!

00:42:00.210 --> 00:42:02.710
I'm sure that's
not what she said.

00:42:02.710 --> 00:42:04.145
Theodore!

00:42:04.145 --> 00:42:05.020
Turn that music down.

00:42:05.020 --> 00:42:08.230
So he grabbed the
record and thus was

00:42:08.230 --> 00:42:09.890
invented the baby scratch.

00:42:09.890 --> 00:42:14.500
And that's what they say how
the scratch was invented.

00:42:14.500 --> 00:42:17.130
Of course, Grand Wizard
Theodore extended this technique

00:42:17.130 --> 00:42:20.230
with various variations
of that scratch

00:42:20.230 --> 00:42:23.570
and made it into a
rhythmic technique.

00:42:23.570 --> 00:42:25.780
Now Grandmaster
Flash provides us

00:42:25.780 --> 00:42:27.360
with some really
excellent examples

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:29.800
of scratching techniques.

00:42:29.800 --> 00:42:33.450
He was known for extending
numerous techniques,

00:42:33.450 --> 00:42:35.980
for developing his
own electronics.

00:42:35.980 --> 00:42:38.500
He built some basic
electronics, and some

00:42:38.500 --> 00:42:41.980
say that he invented, or at
least refined, the cross fader

00:42:41.980 --> 00:42:43.530
itself.

00:42:43.530 --> 00:42:46.200
He, like many
turntablists, came up

00:42:46.200 --> 00:42:47.710
with names for his techniques.

00:42:47.710 --> 00:42:50.590
He describes something
called the quick mix theory,

00:42:50.590 --> 00:42:53.090
or sometimes called a back spin
technique, which is actually

00:42:53.090 --> 00:42:56.750
very similar to Herc's
merry go around.

00:42:56.750 --> 00:42:59.540
He also describes techniques
such as the punch phase where

00:42:59.540 --> 00:43:02.340
he would drop in
and out of a record

00:43:02.340 --> 00:43:05.700
to sort of grab
one sample from it.

00:43:05.700 --> 00:43:08.630
His well known
composition, "Adventures

00:43:08.630 --> 00:43:10.650
of Grandmaster Flash
on the Wheels of Steel"

00:43:10.650 --> 00:43:13.280
was one of our listenings
for this class.

00:43:13.280 --> 00:43:16.628
Let's listen to a little
bit of that to remind us.

00:43:16.628 --> 00:43:16.943
[MUSIC - GRANDMASTER FLASH, "THE
ADVENTURES OF GRANDMASTER FLASH

00:43:16.943 --> 00:43:17.943
ON THE WHEELS OF STEEL"]

00:43:36.430 --> 00:43:37.805
PROFESSOR: So
we've already heard

00:43:37.805 --> 00:43:46.090
him switch between three
or four different records.

00:43:46.090 --> 00:43:48.710
He was also dropping in and
out doing that punch phase

00:43:48.710 --> 00:43:50.730
technique.

00:43:50.730 --> 00:43:53.060
I think that was
the queen example.

00:43:53.060 --> 00:43:54.830
In another interview
with Terry Gross,

00:43:54.830 --> 00:43:57.670
Grandmaster Flash
narrates his techniques

00:43:57.670 --> 00:44:00.370
as he listens to this
