Did it have coherence,
or did it sound

01:02:28.910 --> 01:02:31.810
like it was wandering just
scratching and revving

01:02:31.810 --> 01:02:32.520
over the place?

01:02:32.520 --> 01:02:34.610
AUDIENCE: You heard
the repetition

01:02:34.610 --> 01:02:37.455
and some special motifs
going back and forth,

01:02:37.455 --> 01:02:39.704
so it definitely had
some musical qualities.

01:02:39.704 --> 01:02:40.370
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:02:40.370 --> 01:02:43.160
Anybody else hear anything
in particular in this?

01:02:43.160 --> 01:02:46.450
I think this is a really great
example because in many ways

01:02:46.450 --> 01:02:50.620
it shows what we've seen
many times in our look

01:02:50.620 --> 01:02:51.840
at music and technology.

01:02:51.840 --> 01:02:55.870
It shows an attention to
an economy of resources.

01:02:55.870 --> 01:02:59.340
Using a small bit of
something and extending it out

01:02:59.340 --> 01:03:02.360
and manipulating it
in a variety of ways.

01:03:02.360 --> 01:03:03.297
The opening solo here.

01:03:03.297 --> 01:03:04.796
[MUSIC - D-STYLES, "FELONIUS
 FUNK"]

01:03:07.085 --> 01:03:08.710
PROFESSOR: After this
little part here.

01:03:14.960 --> 01:03:17.930
This whole passage from here
to the end of this phrase

01:03:17.930 --> 01:03:21.930
is all one phrase,
someone saying, oh my god.

01:03:21.930 --> 01:03:24.140
So it's a woman
saying, oh my god,

01:03:24.140 --> 01:03:26.140
and the DJ is
scratching that one

01:03:26.140 --> 01:03:28.140
phrase for this entire passage.

01:03:28.140 --> 01:03:29.550
And in a way it's
sort of a game.

01:03:29.550 --> 01:03:33.410
You start to hear the words come
out until finally at the end

01:03:33.410 --> 01:03:34.814
you hear it very clearly.

01:03:34.814 --> 01:03:36.314
[MUSIC - D-STYLES, "FELONIUS
 FUNK"]

01:03:46.594 --> 01:03:48.260
PROFESSOR: The
[? goddess ?] transformed

01:03:48.260 --> 01:03:49.920
into the melodic passage, yeah.

01:04:17.090 --> 01:04:22.360
So three words used as a sonic
and motific source, carefully

01:04:22.360 --> 01:04:25.090
deployed, built
upon, and extended

01:04:25.090 --> 01:04:27.970
to create what, I think,
is a very coherent solo.

01:04:27.970 --> 01:04:29.710
We hear in the next solo--

01:04:29.710 --> 01:04:32.220
[MUSIC - D-STYLES, "FELONIUS
 FUNK"]

01:04:32.220 --> 01:04:34.220
PROFESSOR: What is the
phrase being cut up here?

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:38.092
Say what.

01:04:38.092 --> 01:04:42.028
[MUSIC - D-STYLES, "FELONIUS
 FUNK"]

01:04:57.929 --> 01:04:59.720
PROFESSOR: Everybody
hear it now, say what.

01:04:59.720 --> 01:05:02.980
Again this economy
of resources, this

01:05:02.980 --> 01:05:06.694
using a small bit of
material as a source

01:05:06.694 --> 01:05:08.360
for an extended
composition is something

01:05:08.360 --> 01:05:11.585
you've seen time and time
again, in many of the works

01:05:11.585 --> 01:05:12.460
that we've looked at.

01:05:12.460 --> 01:05:14.490
Think of Hugh Le
Caine's "Dripsody"

01:05:14.490 --> 01:05:16.710
a composition that
used one sample,

01:05:16.710 --> 01:05:19.820
one taped piece of
sound as a source

01:05:19.820 --> 01:05:21.660
for the entire composition.

01:05:21.660 --> 01:05:25.210
Think of the rigorous
application of tape techniques

01:05:25.210 --> 01:05:27.590
by Cage or others.

01:05:27.590 --> 01:05:31.260
This idea of using a small bit
of material and extending it

01:05:31.260 --> 01:05:35.460
is so common in the
tradition of music and one

01:05:35.460 --> 01:05:38.802
then we see here employed
on the turntable.

01:05:38.802 --> 01:05:40.510
Now the last thing
we're going to look at

01:05:40.510 --> 01:05:44.040
is what I consider the sort of
abstraction of the turntable,

01:05:44.040 --> 01:05:48.804
pulling out the most essential
feature of the turntable.

01:05:48.804 --> 01:05:50.470
And as we talked about
in the beginning,

01:05:50.470 --> 01:05:54.230
the most essential features
seem to be the ability

01:05:54.230 --> 01:05:58.450
to control the speed of a
rotating disc that combined

01:05:58.450 --> 01:06:00.420
with a mixer and a cross fader.

01:06:00.420 --> 01:06:03.730
But this idea of a
rotating disk that

01:06:03.730 --> 01:06:09.810
somehow gives a useful interface
for controlling musical time.

01:06:09.810 --> 01:06:13.800
One reason the rotating disc
is useful for controlling

01:06:13.800 --> 01:06:16.950
musical time is because
it has momentum.

01:06:16.950 --> 01:06:19.220
When you have a
rotating disc, there's

01:06:19.220 --> 01:06:23.490
a very tactile connection,
and you gradually

01:06:23.490 --> 01:06:25.510
can speed it up or slow it down.

01:06:25.510 --> 01:06:28.140
It has a sense of
momentum because it's

01:06:28.140 --> 01:06:31.100
going so that it takes
force to slow it down.

01:06:31.100 --> 01:06:34.370
And if you let go it
gradually speeds up.

01:06:34.370 --> 01:06:38.910
That issue of momentum of
rotation tied to musical time

01:06:38.910 --> 01:06:40.120
is very important.

01:06:40.120 --> 01:06:42.640
It's not found on a
digital audio file.

01:06:42.640 --> 01:06:45.130
We can start and stop
a digital audio file.

01:06:45.130 --> 01:06:49.190
There is no momentum to the
playback of digital audio,

01:06:49.190 --> 01:06:53.730
unless of course we build
models that incorporate that.

01:06:53.730 --> 01:06:56.420
So various approaches
have been proposed

01:06:56.420 --> 01:07:01.860
to keep this rotating disc, this
rotating platter, available.

01:07:01.860 --> 01:07:05.310
This Technics SL
D7-1200, this device

01:07:05.310 --> 01:07:07.290
seems to be
discontinued, allowed

01:07:07.290 --> 01:07:11.530
you to enter a CD into this slot
here and control its play back

01:07:11.530 --> 01:07:13.210
with the rotating disk.

01:07:13.210 --> 01:07:16.780
This is very much like
the SL-1200 turntable.

01:07:16.780 --> 01:07:20.180
It's the exact same
platter, but the platter,

01:07:20.180 --> 01:07:23.600
notice there's no tone arm,
there's no record needle,

01:07:23.600 --> 01:07:26.980
the platter is controlling,
exclusively, the playback

01:07:26.980 --> 01:07:30.940
of the content found on a disc.

01:07:30.940 --> 01:07:34.370
Another approach, this
one by TASCAM, the TTM 1

01:07:34.370 --> 01:07:38.370
uses a little component
to ride on the disc

01:07:38.370 --> 01:07:40.150
and track its motion.

01:07:40.150 --> 01:07:43.750
That tracked motion of
the rotation of the disk,

01:07:43.750 --> 01:07:46.520
again, incorporating any
changes in playback speed

01:07:46.520 --> 01:07:50.770
by the operator, is used to
provide a control signal that

01:07:50.770 --> 01:07:54.650
works only with their
proprietary CD players found

01:07:54.650 --> 01:07:55.290
here.

01:07:55.290 --> 01:07:58.200
But this allows you
to use the turntable

01:07:58.200 --> 01:08:01.303
as a controller for the playback
of stored digital audio.

01:08:01.303 --> 01:08:03.594
AUDIENCE: It looks like the
most expensive possible way

01:08:03.594 --> 01:08:05.280
to do that.

01:08:05.280 --> 01:08:08.440
PROFESSOR: Expensive, well,
and also probably error

01:08:08.440 --> 01:08:09.440
prone, right?

01:08:09.440 --> 01:08:11.780
Because you could
imagine the contact here

01:08:11.780 --> 01:08:13.560
may not be very reliable.

01:08:13.560 --> 01:08:15.060
This wheel might slip.

01:08:15.060 --> 01:08:17.939
They still make this product.

01:08:17.939 --> 01:08:22.370
The approach that has found
the most widespread use

01:08:22.370 --> 01:08:23.600
goes under various names.

01:08:23.600 --> 01:08:25.459
It's now owned by the
Rane Corporations.

01:08:25.459 --> 01:08:27.439
It's called Serato Scratch.

01:08:27.439 --> 01:08:28.960
There's various
versions of this,

01:08:28.960 --> 01:08:30.750
but the way that
this system works

01:08:30.750 --> 01:08:33.347
is you use your
conventional turntables

01:08:33.347 --> 01:08:35.180
that you've invested
hundreds of dollars in.

01:08:35.180 --> 01:08:38.529
You use your mixer which you've
already invested a lot of money

01:08:38.529 --> 01:08:39.100
in.

01:08:39.100 --> 01:08:42.890
But instead of playing records
that have music on them,

01:08:42.890 --> 01:08:45.830
you play records that have
a specially encoded control

01:08:45.830 --> 01:08:46.609
signal.

01:08:46.609 --> 01:08:49.540
This control signal
is tracked out

01:08:49.540 --> 01:08:53.680
of the output of the
turntables by the computer.

01:08:53.680 --> 01:08:56.460
The control signal is
formatted in a way such

01:08:56.460 --> 01:08:59.140
that variations in
playback speed which

01:08:59.140 --> 01:09:02.930
may result by you changing the
playback speed with the slider

01:09:02.930 --> 01:09:06.279
or by scratching are
captured by the computer

01:09:06.279 --> 01:09:09.779
and can be applied to
any digital audio file.

01:09:09.779 --> 01:09:12.910
So this allows you to
use your old turntables

01:09:12.910 --> 01:09:18.859
as control surface for
digital audio files stored

01:09:18.859 --> 01:09:20.529
on your computer in any format.

01:09:20.529 --> 01:09:24.504
This literally lets
you scratch your MP3s.

01:09:24.504 --> 01:09:28.974
AUDIENCE: Do you think that
still has the problem of wear?

01:09:28.974 --> 01:09:32.350
Old discs wear out and then you
still have to buy more records.

01:09:32.350 --> 01:09:33.020
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:09:33.020 --> 01:09:35.460
But I think it's more
probably more accurate,

01:09:35.460 --> 01:09:37.950
and these control records
are relatively inexpensive

01:09:37.950 --> 01:09:40.120
and probably last as
long as any record does.

01:09:40.120 --> 01:09:41.723
So it may not be
a major concern.

01:09:41.723 --> 01:09:43.264
AUDIENCE: Do you
know of anyone who's

01:09:43.264 --> 01:09:45.579
used the degradation of
these control devices.

01:09:45.579 --> 01:09:46.370
PROFESSOR: I don't.

01:09:46.370 --> 01:09:49.020
But that's a really
interesting thing to look at.

01:09:49.020 --> 01:09:53.084
I don't also know exactly how
the control signal is encoded.

01:09:53.084 --> 01:09:54.500
We could imagine
a couple of ways.

01:09:54.500 --> 01:09:57.750
It could be some sort of
binary spacing of clicks

01:09:57.750 --> 01:10:00.642
that it looks at, how close
the clicks get together.

01:10:00.642 --> 01:10:02.350
They might try another
approach, but it's

01:10:02.350 --> 01:10:05.500
interesting to think about
how that system works.

01:10:05.500 --> 01:10:07.730
The control software
for this is fantastic.

01:10:07.730 --> 01:10:11.270
It not only shows
you the waveforms

01:10:11.270 --> 01:10:14.410
coming through which makes
it easy to beat match

01:10:14.410 --> 01:10:16.640
by matching up the
lines here, and it

01:10:16.640 --> 01:10:22.860
lets you queue up other songs
for each virtual turntable

01:10:22.860 --> 01:10:24.740
and do a lot of
other fun things.

01:10:24.740 --> 01:10:26.890
If you go to guitar center,
go to the DJ section,

01:10:26.890 --> 01:10:29.300
you can try this out,
it's quite a bit of fun.

01:10:29.300 --> 01:10:31.700
Now that's expensive
because you still

01:10:31.700 --> 01:10:34.630
have to have real
turntables, and a lot of DJs

01:10:34.630 --> 01:10:36.310
really like this
approach because they

01:10:36.310 --> 01:10:39.010
can use their
existing turntables.

01:10:39.010 --> 01:10:42.290
Furthermore, if they
want to combine a vinyl

01:10:42.290 --> 01:10:45.900
disc on one turntable and a
digital audio file on another,

01:10:45.900 --> 01:10:49.670
they can mix and match with
the Serato Scratch system

01:10:49.670 --> 01:10:54.430
Other sort of hybrid systems
are things like this Numark NS-7

01:10:54.430 --> 01:11:02.030
which combines-- notice these
are 78 size disc-- which

01:11:02.030 --> 01:11:02.980
combines this.

01:11:02.980 --> 01:11:06.970
Notice there's also
no tone arm here.

01:11:06.970 --> 01:11:10.970
So this device provides
an integrated control

01:11:10.970 --> 01:11:12.450
where you can
control the playback

01:11:12.450 --> 01:11:14.260
speed with these discs.

01:11:14.260 --> 01:11:16.200
The mixer and other
tools are built in,

01:11:16.200 --> 01:11:20.040
but again, it's all
controlling digital audio

01:11:20.040 --> 01:11:21.610
stored on the computer.

01:11:21.610 --> 01:11:26.080
Here, presumably, the actual
movement of the platter

01:11:26.080 --> 01:11:27.780
is what is used to
control the playback

01:11:27.780 --> 01:11:29.640
speed of the digital audio.

01:11:29.640 --> 01:11:31.240
But this, again,
is another approach

01:11:31.240 --> 01:11:35.690
of abstracting out this
essential feature of momentum

01:11:35.690 --> 01:11:39.170
based playback model.

01:11:39.170 --> 01:11:41.780
So I like to look at what
we've looked at here as sort

01:11:41.780 --> 01:11:45.910
of trajectory from
first coercion.

01:11:45.910 --> 01:11:48.790
Taking a device that
was not intended

01:11:48.790 --> 01:11:52.040
to be used as a
soloistic instrument

01:11:52.040 --> 01:11:54.610
and refining the
number of techniques

01:11:54.610 --> 01:11:58.220
out of this process of
coercion and then, now

01:11:58.220 --> 01:12:00.900
that that's sort of
solidified, what would the term

01:12:00.900 --> 01:12:03.250
be that Biker might
give to that sort

01:12:03.250 --> 01:12:04.475
of the scratching techniques?

01:12:04.475 --> 01:12:07.010
Sort of reach a
sense of closure,

01:12:07.010 --> 01:12:09.630
we see a sort of
next stage where

01:12:09.630 --> 01:12:12.290
now the essential
features of the turntable

01:12:12.290 --> 01:12:15.270
are being abstracted,
pulled out, and made

01:12:15.270 --> 01:12:17.420
into a number of
devices that provide

01:12:17.420 --> 01:12:20.300
similar control but a
totally different playback

01:12:20.300 --> 01:12:22.760
mechanism that is
reading digital audio off

01:12:22.760 --> 01:12:26.300
of a computer or
other stored data.

01:12:26.300 --> 01:12:26.800
Ideas?

01:12:29.950 --> 01:12:34.200
Can you imagine other types
of momentum based controllers

01:12:34.200 --> 01:12:37.440
we might have if we imagine
what the next stage.

01:12:37.440 --> 01:12:42.270
Will people continue to
use things like Serato

01:12:42.270 --> 01:12:44.010
with conventional
turntables, or might we

01:12:44.010 --> 01:12:46.360
imagine other
interfaces that will

01:12:46.360 --> 01:12:49.110
allow DJs to do what
they've done for the last 30

01:12:49.110 --> 01:12:52.237
or 40 years but in
alternative ways?

01:12:52.237 --> 01:12:53.820
AUDIENCE: Like surface
tables that you

01:12:53.820 --> 01:12:57.942
could sort of show
images and work off that.

01:12:57.942 --> 01:12:58.900
PROFESSOR: That's true.

01:12:58.900 --> 01:13:01.483
I mean, we do see this interest
in touch screens and the like,

01:13:01.483 --> 01:13:04.660
and you could
visualize the screen.

01:13:04.660 --> 01:13:06.370
But I think the
problem there would

01:13:06.370 --> 01:13:10.410
be that you don't have momentum,
you can't feel the speed,

01:13:10.410 --> 01:13:12.860
and I think that's a
very important feature

01:13:12.860 --> 01:13:14.072
of turntablism.

01:13:14.072 --> 01:13:15.530
And I think that's
something that's

01:13:15.530 --> 01:13:18.080
retained in the abstractions
that we see there.

01:13:18.080 --> 01:13:22.370
I think that really illustrates
a good point because there's

01:13:22.370 --> 01:13:24.580
something in the contact,
in that sense of momentum

01:13:24.580 --> 01:13:26.820
of having to physically
spinning disc,

01:13:26.820 --> 01:13:28.810
that seems to be really
important to turntable

01:13:28.810 --> 01:13:29.310
practice.

01:13:29.310 --> 01:13:30.605
AUDIENCE: Do all of those
actually rotate though?

01:13:30.605 --> 01:13:32.474
I know some of the
CD DJ interfaces

01:13:32.474 --> 01:13:33.390
don't actually rotate.

01:13:33.390 --> 01:13:35.880
PROFESSOR: Some don't rotate.

01:13:35.880 --> 01:13:37.360
There are some
that don't rotate.

01:13:37.360 --> 01:13:40.580
They just give you a big
button that you can move,

01:13:40.580 --> 01:13:43.100
but it doesn't seem like DJs
are really attracted to those.

01:13:43.100 --> 01:13:44.730
The ones that DJs
seem to be attracted

01:13:44.730 --> 01:13:47.250
are the ones that actually
represent playback time

01:13:47.250 --> 01:13:51.190
in some sort of
rotational sense.

01:13:51.190 --> 01:13:53.710
Other ideas?

01:13:53.710 --> 01:13:55.180
AUDIENCE: What about DJ Hero?

01:13:55.180 --> 01:13:57.890
PROFESSOR: DJ Hero,
how does that work?

01:13:57.890 --> 01:14:00.680
AUDIENCE: It's one
turntable, a cross fader,

01:14:00.680 --> 01:14:03.170
the turntable has
buttons on it, and you

01:14:03.170 --> 01:14:05.460
scratch like the
two outer buttons

01:14:05.460 --> 01:14:07.320
you hold down while scratching.

01:14:07.320 --> 01:14:08.840
And that's how you can--

01:14:08.840 --> 01:14:11.735
PROFESSOR: Do you have to move
the cross fader to succeed?

01:14:11.735 --> 01:14:12.630
Do you have to--

01:14:12.630 --> 01:14:15.164
AUDIENCE: Move the cross
fader into the three positions

01:14:15.164 --> 01:14:15.984
or whatever.

01:14:15.984 --> 01:14:18.400
But the weird thing with the
scratching is it doesn't spin

01:14:18.400 --> 01:14:19.328
or anything.

01:14:19.328 --> 01:14:21.542
It's a lightweight
turntable hand.

01:14:21.542 --> 01:14:23.500
It's hard to press a
button and scratch a thing

01:14:23.500 --> 01:14:24.840
at the same time.

01:14:24.840 --> 01:14:26.690
PROFESSOR: That's great.

01:14:26.690 --> 01:14:30.650
Well you can all play DJ Hero
or just go to guitar center

01:14:30.650 --> 01:14:31.930
and tryout Serato Scratch.

01:14:31.930 --> 01:14:32.860
It's really fun.

01:14:32.860 --> 01:14:35.910
Great, I'll see
you guys next time.

